         <entryFree xml:id="k000290" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000290-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">shunjichuan</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000290-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">顺脊串</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000290-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">顺脊串</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000290-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">shùnjǐchuàn</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000290-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">shun-chi-ch`uan</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000290-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000290-1" >along-ridge tie</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000290</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p>under construction</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">Shunjichuan 順脊串 is a type of tie beam (<term ref="/keyword/k000289">chuan 串</term>) in traditional Chinese architecture. As an architectural term, shunjichuan first appeared in Yingzao fashi during the 
                  <term ref="/keyword/k000074">Song</term> dynasty (Li, 2009, 5.7a). According to the Yingzao fashi, shunjichuan is a linking element located beneath the ridge purlin (jituan 脊槫) and the shuzhu 蜀柱 (lit. dwarf pillar), 
                  with its height positioned at the center of the shuzhu. The sectional dimension of shunjichuan is typically as high and wide as a standard dancai 單材（15 fen 分 high and 10 fen wide), 
                  or may be 3-4 fen larger. In the minor carpentry system (xiaomuzuo 小木作), shunjichuan is referred to as jichuan 脊串. The earliest existing example of the use of shunjichuan is in the 
                  <term ref="/place/000158">Amitabha Hall (Mituodian 彌陀殿)</term> at Dayunyuan in Pingshun, Shanxi, dating from 940 during the <term ref="/keyword/k000026">Five Dynasties</term> period.</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">順脊串是串的一種，作為建築構件的名稱最早出現在宋《營造法式》（李誡2009，5.7a）。根據《營造法式》，順脊串是位於脊槫下穿插於蜀柱間的聯繫構件，施用高度位於蜀柱中心，斷面廣厚如材（15分x10分），
                  或加3-4分，在小木作中順脊串被簡稱為“脊串”。現存最早使用順脊串的建築實例是五代的平順大雲院彌陀殿（940年）。</p>
            </note>
